On Sat, Jun 21, 2003 at 02:56:15AM -0000, Nelson wrote:


&gt; Usually when I build my TestSuite, I do something akin to 
&gt; 
&gt; 	TestSuite suite= new TestSuite(&quot;All JUnit Tests&quot;);
&gt; 	suite.addTest(com.foo1.AllTests.suite());
&gt; 	suite.addTest(com.foo2.AllTests.suite());
&gt; 
&gt; then I run the testrunner.
&gt; 
&gt; This works fine because I only have two packages I&#39;m testing here.
&gt; But every package I add, that means I&#39;d have to add an AllTests class
&gt; for that package, then make sure that new AllTests class takes care of
&gt; it&#39;s subordinate classes and packages as well.
&gt; 
&gt; This is slightly mechanical and painstaking *every* time I make a new
&gt; package or class.
&gt; 
&gt; Is there a more automated way JUnit can traverse through a package
&gt; tree, and find all the classes that implement suite(), and
&gt; automatically call them for me?

I run testcases with:

    &lt;junit printsummary=&quot;yes&quot; haltonfailure=&quot;no&quot; fork=&quot;no&quot; showoutput=&quot;true&quot;&gt;
      &lt;formatter type=&quot;xml&quot; usefile=&quot;true&quot;/&gt;
      &lt;batchtest todir=&quot;${reports.junit}&quot;&gt;
        &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${build.test}&quot;&gt;
    	    &lt;include name=&quot;**/*TestCase.class&quot;/&gt;
        	&lt;include name=&quot;**/*Test.class&quot; /&gt;
        	&lt;exclude name=&quot;**/Abstract*.class&quot; /&gt;
	    &lt;/fileset&gt;
      &lt;/batchtest&gt;
    &lt;/junit&gt;

This works fine for me - this traverse through a package tree, and find
all tests and automatically call them :)


